    "what_description": "Curcuma longa is a perennial plant belonging to the family Zingiberaceae, native to India and Southeast Asia. It is characterized by its thick, short rhizome, which is the edible part of the plant, and its long, narrow leaves that are dark green in color and have a waxy texture. The plant can grow up to 3 feet tall, with a spread of up to 1.5 feet, and has a branched, woody stem. The rhizome of Curcuma longa is the source of turmeric, a spice widely used in cooking and medicine, and is rich in compounds such as curcumin, demethoxycurcumin, and bisdemethoxycurcumin. The plant flowers in late summer, producing funnel-shaped purple flowers with a yellow base.",
